<h1>Active Directory in Azure</h1>
This tutorial outlines the implementation of Active Directory using Azure Virtual Machines.<br />


<h2>Environments and Technologies Used</h2>

- Microsoft Azure (Virtual Machines/Compute)
- Remote Desktop
- Active Directory Domain Services
- PowerShell

<h2>Operating Systems Used </h2>

- Windows Server 2022
- Windows 10 (21H2)

<h2>High-Level Deployment and Configuration Steps</h2>

- Step 1.) Setting up resources in Azure.
- Step 2.) Ensuring Connectivity between Domain Controller(DC1) and Client Virtual Machines(Client1).
- Step 3.) Active Directory Setup on Domain Controller (DC1)
- Step 4.) Joining Client1 to Domain.
- Step 5.) Setup Remote Desktop for non-administrative users on Client-1.
- Step 6.) Create multiple additional users using Powershell, and log into Client1 using one of the addedd users.

<h2> Step 1: Setting up Resources in Azure</h2>

<p>
<img src="https://imgur.com/zNW2qZj" height="80%" width="80%" alt="Disk Sanitization Steps"/>
<img src="https://imgur.com/2fumgSc"
</p>
<p>
For this tutorial, we will be setting up two Virtual Machines in Azure. One of the virtual machines will serve as the Domain Controller, and the other will act as a client or user PC that can be used by someone within the domain.

Step 1: Create both Virtual Machines in Azure.
Domain Controller: Name: DC1, Operating System: Windows Server 2022
Client / User PC: Name: Client1, Operating System: Windows 10
</p>
<br />

